    "intro": "Interpretation asks what the text means — moving from observation (what does it say?) to discerning the author's intent in his original context. The movements below trace the chapter's argument through its four rhetorical acts: theophanic petition, corporate confession, potter-clay appeal, and lament-evidence. Where the Hebrew sharpens or alters the English, a Greek note (using Hebrew transliterations in this Old Testament context) supplements the exposition.",
