        "body": "The pivot 'Behold, You were angry, for we sinned' (64:5b) is the chapter's most important hermeneutical turn. Having established God's unique capacity to act (64:4), the community immediately confesses why He has not done so: persistent sin has provoked justified anger. The question 'Shall we be saved?' (64:5b) is not rhetorical — it is the anxious moral question of people who know exactly what they deserve and are not certain grace extends this far.\n\nVerse 6 contains the Old Testament's most concentrated expression of what Reformed theology will later call *total depravity*. Four movements: (1) 'All of us have become like one who is unclean' — universal defilement, using Levitical impurity language. (2) 'All our righteous deeds are like a filthy garment' — the Hebrew *beged iddah* is literally 'a garment of menstruation,' the strongest ritual impurity image available. Note carefully: this is not describing Israel's sins but their *righteous deeds*. The moral corruption is so comprehensive that even the community's best offerings are defiled. Jonathan Edwards, in *Religious Affections*, drew on this verse to argue that human moral effort, apart from regeneration, produces what appears to be virtue but is inwardly corrupted by self-interest and unclean motives. (3) 'We all wither like a leaf' — frailty and mortality attend the sin-condition. (4) 'Our iniquities, like the wind, take us away' — not passive drift but active removal; sin as an external force that carries the sinner away from God.\n\nVerse 7 completes the diagnosis with the darkest note in the chapter: 'There is no one who calls on Your name, who arouses himself to take hold of You.' The same verb *ur* (arouse, stir up) is used of stirring embers to fire — here, not a single person has the spiritual vitality to kindle even the beginning of a return to God. This is the Old Testament equivalent of Romans 3:11 ('there is none who seeks for God') and Ephesians 2:1 ('dead in your trespasses and sins'). The spiritual paralysis is total. And the ground given: 'For You have hidden Your face from us and have delivered us into the power of our iniquities.' God's sovereign concealment and the community's own moral entrapment are both operative — neither is retracted. The only exit from this spiral requires someone outside the community to act.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Beged iddah* (filthy garment, 64:6) — Levitical impurity at its strongest register (Leviticus 15:19-30). *Naval* (wither, 64:6) — to fall, to fade, used of flowers and leaves in Isaiah 1:30; 40:7-8. *Satar* (hidden, 64:7) — to conceal, same root as *hester panim* (hiddenness of God's face), a major theological category in the Psalms and Lamentations."
