        "body": "The 'But now, O Lord' of verse 8 is the chapter's hinge — structurally, theologically, and pastorally. In Hebrew, *ve'attah* ('but now, and you') marks a decisive turn in Old Testament prayer and argument. Daniel uses it (Daniel 9:15); Nehemiah uses it (Nehemiah 9:32); Ezra uses it (Ezra 9:10). The grammar signals: everything said up to this point is true; but here is the one thing that changes the conclusion. The one thing in Isaiah 64:8 is not a new argument — it is the oldest relationship: 'You are our Father.'\n\nThe potter-clay metaphor (64:8b) is drawn from Jeremiah 18:1-11 and echoes the creation narrative of Genesis 2:7 where God *forms* (*yatsar*) man from dust — the same verb as 'potter.' The claim is not sentimental: it is ontological. The community is arguing that God's creative act has established a relationship that Israel's sin cannot annul, because it does not rest on Israel's performance but on God's act of forming. John Calvin commented on this verse: 'The petitioner does not boast of any merit, but casts himself wholly on the goodness of God, pleading that we are the work of His hands and therefore He cannot abandon us without abandoning the work of His own creation.' This is precisely the move: the appeal bypasses the question of merit entirely and goes to origin.\n\nVerse 9 translates the metaphor into concrete petition: 'Do not be angry beyond measure, O Lord, nor remember iniquity forever; behold, look now, all of us are Your people.' Three requests, each calibrated: (1) not anger *beyond measure* — not the removal of justified anger, but its proportionate limitation; (2) not remember iniquity *forever* — again, not the denial that iniquity exists, but the temporal limitation of its hold; (3) 'behold, look upon us, we pray' — the imperative to turn the divine gaze back toward this community. 'All of us are Your people' is the final covenant argument: not we are righteous, not we have earned this, but — we are Yours.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Attah* (but now, 64:8) — the classic OT prayer-pivot. *Yatsar* (potter, 64:8) — to form, to mold, the same verb as Genesis 2:7 and Isaiah 43:1. *Chomer* (clay) — the raw material, also used for mortar; its connotation of formlessness underscores utter dependence. *Zakhar* (remember, 64:9) — covenantal memory that triggers action; the petition asks God to remember relationship, not transgression."
